A **WebSocket** is a **communication protocol** that enables **real‑time, two‑way (bi‑directional) communication** between a **client (browser/app)** and a **server** over a **single, long‑lived connection**.

It is designed to solve the limitations of traditional HTTP for real‑time applications.

***

## ✅ Simple Definition (Interview‑Ready)

> **WebSocket is a protocol that provides full‑duplex communication between client and server over a persistent connection, enabling real‑time data exchange.**

***

## ✅ Why WebSocket Exists (The Problem with HTTP)

### ❌ HTTP (Traditional)

*   Client sends a request
*   Server responds
*   Connection closes (stateless)
*   Client must **poll repeatedly** for updates

Example:

```text
Client → Request
Server → Response
(Client keeps asking again and again)
```

❌ Inefficient  
❌ High latency  
❌ Wasted network resources

***

### ✅ WebSocket (Solution)

*   **Single persistent connection**
*   Both client **and** server can send data anytime

```text
Client ⇆ Server (always open connection)
```

✅ Real‑time  
✅ Low latency  
✅ Efficient

***

## ✅ Key Features of WebSocket

| Feature               | Description                         |
| --------------------- | ----------------------------------- |
| Full‑duplex           | Client & server talk simultaneously |
| Persistent connection | Stays open                          |
| Low latency           | No repeated handshakes              |
| Event‑driven          | Data pushed instantly               |
| Protocol              | `ws://` or `wss://`                 |

***

## ✅ WebSocket vs HTTP (Very Important)

| Feature    | HTTP             | WebSocket       |
| ---------- | ---------------- | --------------- |
| Connection | Short‑lived      | Persistent      |
| Direction  | Client → Server  | Client ⇆ Server |
| Real‑time  | ❌ No             | ✅ Yes           |
| Overhead   | High             | Low             |
| Use case   | Request/response | Live data       |

***

## ✅ Common Use Cases

✅ Chat applications (WhatsApp, Slack)  
✅ Live notifications  
✅ Stock market updates  
✅ Online games  
✅ Live dashboards  
✅ Collaborative editing (Google Docs)

***

## ✅ How WebSocket Works (Flow)

1️⃣ Client makes an **HTTP handshake request**  
2️⃣ Server upgrades protocol to **WebSocket**  
3️⃣ Connection stays open  
4️⃣ Both sides exchange messages freely

***

## ✅ WebSocket Handshake Example

**Request**

```http
GET /chat HTTP/1.1
Upgrade: websocket
Connection: Upgrade
```

**Response**

```http
HTTP/1.1 101 Switching Protocols
Upgrade: websocket
Connection: Upgrade
```

***

## ✅ WebSocket Code Example (Browser)

### ✅ Client Side

```js
const socket = new WebSocket("ws://localhost:8080");

socket.onopen = () => {
  console.log("Connected");
  socket.send("Hello Server");
};

socket.onmessage = (event) => {
  console.log("Received:", event.data);
};

socket.onclose = () => {
  console.log("Disconnected");
};
```

***

### ✅ Server Side (Node.js example conceptually)

```js
const WebSocket = require("ws");

const server = new WebSocket.Server({ port: 8080 });

server.on("connection", socket => {
  socket.on("message", message => {
    socket.send(`Echo: ${message}`);
  });
});
```

***

## ✅ WebSocket Security

*   `ws://` → Not secure
*   `wss://` → Secure (uses TLS/HTTPS)

✅ Always use **`wss://`** in production

***

## ✅ WebSocket vs Polling vs SSE (Interview Topic)

| Technique | Direction       | Real‑time | Efficiency |
| --------- | --------------- | --------- | ---------- |
| Polling   | Client → Server | ❌         | ❌          |
| SSE       | Server → Client | ✅         | ✅          |
| WebSocket | Client ⇆ Server | ✅         | ✅✅         |

✅ **WebSocket is the most powerful**

***

## ✅ Limitations of WebSocket ⚠️

❌ More complex to manage  
❌ Harder to scale  
❌ Needs fallback for older networks  
❌ Not cache‑friendly

